{{For|the Russian footballer|Nikolai Stankevich (footballer)}} {{Infobox philosopher | name = Nikolai Stankevich | birth_name = Nikolai Vladimirovich Stankevich | image = Stankevich.jpg | image_size = <!-- only if smaller than default size --> | alt = | caption = <!-- only if there is useful info, such as a date--> | birth_date = {{birth date|1813|10|09}} | birth_place = Uderevka, [[Voronezh Governorate]] (present-day [[Alexeyevsky District, Belgorod Oblast|Alexeyevsky District]]), [[Russian Empire]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1840|07|07|1813|10|09}} | death_place = [[Novi Ligure]], Italy | region = {{unbulleted list |[[Russian philosophy]] |[[Western philosophy]]}} | era = [[19th century philosophy]] | school_tradition = | main_interests = | influences = [[Friedrich Wilhelm Joseph Schelling|Schelling]], [[Georg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel|Hegel]], [[Johann Gottlieb Fichte|Fichte]] | influenced = [[Vissarion Belinsky|Belinsky]], [[Timofey Granovsky|Granovsky]], [[Mikhail Bakunin|Bakunin]], [[Alexander Herzen|Herzen]] }}
'''Nikolai Vladimirovich Stankevich''' ({{Lang-ru|link=no|Никола́й Влади́мирович Станке́вич}}) ({{OldStyleDate|October 9|1813|September 27}} – {{OldStyleDate|July 7|1840|June 25}}) was a Russian public figure, philosopher, and poet.
==Biography== Nikolay Stankevich was born in [[Alexeyevsky District, Belgorod Oblast|Uderevka]], [[Voronezh Governorate]], and in 1834 graduated from the [[Moscow State University]], where he was influenced by Professor [[Mikhail Kachenovsky]] and followers of the so-called "skeptical school" in [[historiography]]. By late 1831, Stankevich had organized a literary and philosophical society called the ''Circle of Stankevich''. He had been under police surveillance since 1833 due to his connections with a group of oppositionary university students led by Ya.I. Kostenetsky.<ref>Nicholas Hans, ''The Russian Tradition in Education'', [[Routledge]], 2002, p. 32</ref> In 1837, Nikolay Stankevich had to travel abroad due to his [[tuberculosis]].<ref>Paul Bushkovitch, ''A Concise History of Russia'', [[Cambridge University Press]], 2011, p. 162</ref>
Stankevich's literary and esthetical views, most of which mirrored the ideas of a Russian historian [[Nikolai Nadezhdin]], presupposed the humanistic [[Age of Enlightenment|enlightenment]] as the main task of the Russian [[intelligentsia]]. Stankevich is known to have considerably influenced some of the Russian and [[Moscow|Muscovite]] intelligentsia in particular, including [[Vissarion Belinsky]], [[Timofey Granovsky]], [[Mikhail Bakunin]], and [[Alexander Herzen]]. Among Stankevich's literary works (mostly poetic and not numerous), there are a few verses dedicated to Moscow and a historical tragedy called ''Vasili Shuisky''.<ref>[http://www.zpu-journal.ru/en/journal/contents/2012/4/Svalov_Stankevichs-Tragedy-Vasiliy-Shuiskiy/ Svalov A. N. On N. V. Stankevich's Tragedy "Vasiliy Shuiskiy" (The Academy of Social Sciences, Moscow)]</ref>
He died, aged 26, in [[Novi Ligure]], Italy.
