{{Infobox book | name = The Degrees of Knowledge | title_orig = | translator = | image = The Degrees of Knowledge.jpg | image_size = 200px | caption = | author = [[Jacques Maritain]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = France | language = French | series = | subject = [[Epistemology]] | published ={{plainlist| *1932 (in French) *1959 (in English) }} | media_type = Print ([[Hardcover]] and [[Paperback]]) | pages = | isbn = 978-0268008864 | dewey= | congress= | oclc= | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} '''''The Degrees of Knowledge''''' ({{lang-fr|Distinguer pour unir, ou Les Degrés du Savoir}}) is a 1932 book by the philosopher [[Jacques Maritain]], his major contribution to [[epistemology]].<ref>[[#Hal95|Haldane 1995]]. p. 522.</ref> It was first published in English translation in 1959.<ref>[[#Bla94|Blackburn 1994]]. p. 231.</ref>
==Reception== The philosopher [[Adolf Grünbaum]] argued in ''[[Philosophical Problems of Space and Time]]'' (1963) that Maritain presents an unsound and incorrect interpretation of the nature of [[geometry]].<ref>[[#Grü74|Grünbaum 1974]]. pp. 148-150.</ref>
